What is HDL Cholesterol and Why Is It Important? HDL Cholesterol and Why Is It Important? High density lipoprotein or HDL, is considered the “good” cholesterol. HDL is often referred to as “good” cholesterol because it carries cholesterol from the arteries to the liver, where cholesterol is broken down and excreted from the body. High levels of HDL cholesterol have been shown to reduce the risk for heart disease. HDL cholesterol levels are influenced by several factors including age, smoking, gender, and genetics. LDL (low density lipoprotein) is a type of cholesterol that transports cholesterol from the liver to the cells of the body. LDL is often referred to as “bad cholesterol” because it contributes to plaque buildup in arteries, which increases the risk of heart attack and stroke.

LDL levels can be lowered through diet, exercise, and medication.

LDL levels are often screened as part of a routine cholesterol test, along with levels of HDL (“good cholesterol”) and total cholesterol.

What is active listening? In active listening, the listener is actively involved in receiving and interpreting the message. Active listening is a communication technique that requires the listener to pay close attention to the speaker, and provide feedback and ask questions. Active listening is a skill that can be learned, and there are numerous ways to practice active listening. Active listening involves not only paying attention to what is being said, but how it is being said.
